To demonstrate that compound 41 bound to Itk covalently, recombinant Itk was incubated with compound 41 and subjected to analysis by mass spectrometry after digestion with trypsin and chymotrypsin to give short peptide fragments, which were more readily detected by LC-MS/MS. The peptide 434VFEFMEHGCLSDY446 was found to be covalently modified and exhibited a mass increase of 555.27 when compared to the unmodified peptide, which was equal to the mass of compound 41. Furthermore, MS/MS data showed that Cys442 was indeed the modification site (Table 5
                        , Fig. S1). In addition, we designed a probe (compound 46) based on the structure of 9. Probe 46 labeled recombinant Itk and could also react with TAMRA™-azide via copper-catalyzed azide-alkyne cycloaddition [31] for fluorescence detection. Excess compounds 9, 41, and a reported covalent Itk inhibitor, PRN694 [24], but not the reversible inhibitor BMS509774 [32], completely blocked the labeling of Itk by probe 46 (Fig. 5
                        ). These data suggested that compounds 9 and 41 bound Itk covalently and irreversibly.

It was reported that Itk inhibitors showed anti-proliferative effects on T cell lymphoma cells [14–16]. We tested the anti-proliferative effects of compounds 9 and 43. Both compounds potently inhibited malignant cell proliferation (Table 6
                        , Fig. 7
                        ). Further analysis indicated that after incubating Jurkat, CCRF-CEM, and Molt-4 cells with compound 9 for 24 h, levels of caspase-3 and poly ADP-ribose polymerase (PARP) in cells were downregulated, and levels of cleaved PARP were increased, suggesting that compound 9 could induce cell apoptosis (Fig. S3).

Step 3 (
General method A
): Compound S3 (0.3 g, 0.66 mmol), 4-morpholinoaniline (0.12 g, 0.66 mmol), Pd2(dba)3 (0.12 g, 0.13 mmol), Xantphos (0.11 g, 0.2 mmol), NaO-tBu (0.19 g, 1.98 mmol), and 5 mL of toluene were added to a microwave vial, and the mixture was heated in a microwave reactor at 145 °C for 90 min. After cooling, the solution was concentrated under vacuum and the residue was purified by silica flash chromatography. The intermediate product was dissolved in 3 mL of dichloromethane and 3 mL of TFA, and stirred for 4 h at room temperature. The reaction solution was concentrated under vacuum and re-dissolved in 3 mL of ethyl alcohol and 5 drops of water. K2CO3 (0.146 g, 1.06 mmol) was added and the reaction was stirred for 1 h. The reaction mixture was filtered and concentrated under vacuum, then directly purified by silica flash chromatography to yield 12 (0.058 g, 19% for two steps). 1H NMR (400 MHz, DMSO‑d 6) δ 11.72 (s, 1H), 8.87 (s, 1H), 7.75 (d, J = 7.3 Hz, 2H), 7.52–7.39 (m, 4H), 7.35 (t, J = 7.7 Hz, 2H), 7.30 (dd, J = 9.2, 5.2 Hz, 4H), 7.21 (t, J = 7.4 Hz, 1H), 6.68 (d, J = 8.8 Hz, 2H), 3.82–3.64 (m, 4H), 3.07–2.87 (m, 4H). 13C NMR (101 MHz, DMSO‑d 6) δ 164.15, 157.91, 157.12, 154.79, 147.28, 136.68, 135.65, 131.43, 129.94, 127.67, 126.83, 124.01, 121.72, 121.32, 117.88, 117.39, 98.05, 68.06, 51.35. HRMS (m/z) calcd. for C28H26N5O2 ([M+H]+) 464.2087; found 464.2081.
